<DOC><DOCNO> AP880819-0159 </DOCNO><FILEID>AP-NR-08-19-88 1656EDT</FILEID><FIRST>r i AM-Pakistan-Profile     08-19 0320</FIRST><SECOND>AM-Pakistan-Profile,0331</SECOND><HEAD>Ishaq Khan a Third World Economic Diplomat, Cautious Administrator</HEAD><HEAD>With AM-Pakistan Bjt</HEAD><BYLINE>By MOHAMMED AFTAB</BYLINE><BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE><DATELINE>ISLAMABAD, Pakistan (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   Ghulam Ishaq Khan, who became actingpresident with the death of Mohammed Zia ul-Haq, is considered acautious administrator with moderate views on internationaleconomic and financial.   Ishaq Khan, 73, the chairman of the senate, moved into thenation's top position in accordance with the constitution afterZia's death Wednesday.   He served as chairman of the powerful development committee ofthe World Bank and with the International Monetary Fund in theearly 1980s, trying to reach solutions to a number of issuescreating friction between the Third World and Western nations.   At the time, the Third World and the West were squaring off overLatin American debt, plans for development of the impoverishedAfrican Sahara Desert and programs to provide more resources toundeveloped nations.   Ishaq Khan was born Jan. 20, 1915, at Ismail Khel, about 160miles southwest of Islamabad, close to the Afghan border.   He majored in chemistry and botany at the University of thePunjab in Lahore.   He joined the civil service in 1940 in then-British India andwas serving in the North-West Frontier province when Pakistan wonits freedom in 1947. He became the secretary of Pakistan cabinet in1970.   Ishaq Khan was appointed governor of the State Bank of Pakistan,the nation's central bank, in 1971. He later served as defensesecretary, during which time he caught the attention of Zia, whowas army chief of staff.   Zia in 1979 made Ishaq Khan minister for finance, commerce andplanning.   Six years later, the minister was elected to the senate,becoming chairman on March 21, 1985.   Under the constitution, the chairman of parliament's upper housebecomes head of the government when the president is incapacitatedor dies.   The acting president speaks his native Pushtu, Urdu, andEnglish, and has traveled widely.</TEXT></DOC>